{{AfC comment|1=Note: This draft started from a complete copy of [[Onmyōji]] as it has a lot of redlinks with claims I want to keep. I will trim down into just the claim on an individual thing later[[User:Immanuelle|'''Immanuel'''le]] ❤️💚💙 [[User_talk:Immanuelle|(talk to the cutest Wikipedian)]] 01:41, 25 April 2023 (UTC)}}

{{draft}}

{{ill|Onmyō Hakase|lt=Doctor of Onmyō|ja|陰陽博士|1=Onmyō Hakase|qq=draft}} is a topic related to __NOINDEX__  [[Onmyodo]]

Later, [[Emperor Tenmu]] was such a master of astrology and fugue that he took his own divination tools and told fortunes during the [[Jinshin War]]. He also had a deep knowledge of the yin-and-yang five phases philosophy, which led to the establishment of the Bureau of Onmyō and Japan's first [[observatory]] in 676, and the use of the term "onmyōji" in 685, which further increased the popularity of the yin-and-yang five phases philosophy. In 718, the [[Yōrō Code]] established the Bureau of Onmyō as an internal department of the Ministry of Center, and when it was stipulated that the positions of {{ill|Temmon Hakase|lt=Doctor of Astrology|ja|天文博士|1=Tenmon Hakase|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Onmyō Hakase|lt=Doctor of Onmyō|ja|陰陽博士|1=Onmyō Hakase|qq=draft}}, onmyōji, {{ill|Reki Hakase|lt=Doctor of Calendar|ja|暦博士|1=Reki Hakase|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Rōkoku Hakase|lt=Doctor of Water Clock|ja|漏刻博士|1=Rōkoku Hakase|qq=draft}} should be permanently assigned as technical officers, the Bureau of Onmyō became officially in charge of divination along with the [[turtle shell]] diviners who belonged to the [[Department of Divinities]].

{{Cite needed|date=January 2023}}
'''Onmyō Hakase''' ({{ill|陰陽博士|1=Onmyō Hakase|ja|陰陽博士|1=Onmyō Hakase|qq=draft}}) was an instructional position established in the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft}} under Japan's [[Ritsuryō system]]. Its primary role was to educate {{ill|Onmyōji|ja|陰陽師|qq=draft}}. The position was held by one appointee (though there are alternative views on the actual number). It was equivalent to {{ill|Junior Seventh Rank, Lower Grade|ja|正七位下|1=Senior Seventh Rank|lt=Senior Seventh Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft}}.

The role first appeared in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft}} in an entry for {{ill|6th year of Emperor Jitō|ja|692|qq=draft}}, though the {{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|qq=draft}} records for {{ill|5th year of Yōrō|ja|721|qq=draft}} mention two individuals, {{ill|Ōtsu no Kubi|ja|大津首|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Tsumori Michi|ja|津守通|qq=draft}}, serving as Onmyō Hakase, suggesting the position may have had multiple holders. 

The Onmyō Hakase was responsible for educating ten {{ill|Onmyōsei|ja|陰陽生|qq=draft}} students. However, in {{ill|Tenpyō 2|ja|天平2nd year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|730}}), as part of efforts to strengthen the Onmyōryō, three of these students were designated as {{ill|Onmyō Tokugyōsei|ja|陰陽得業生}} and received stipends. These students were subsequently chosen for future positions as Onmyōji and Onmyō Hakase. Additionally, the Hakase was granted four chō (町) of {{ill|Shikiden|ja|職田|qq=draft}} (allotted rice fields). 

Educational texts included {{ill|Shinsen Onmyōshō|ja|新撰陰陽書|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Huangdi Jinkui Jing|ja|黄帝金匱経|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Gogyō Daiyi|ja|五行大義|qq=draft}}, {{ill|I Ching|ja|易経|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Nangi|ja|難儀|qq=draft}}. 

During the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|qq=draft}} and early {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft}}, the position was typically held by members of the {{ill|Ōtsu clan|ja|大津氏|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yuge clan|ja|弓削氏|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Shigatake clan|ja|滋岳氏|qq=draft}}. In the mid-Heian period, the {{ill|Imibe clan|ja|惟宗氏|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Abe clan|ja|阿倍氏|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Kamo clan|ja|賀茂朝臣氏|qq=draft}} became prominent. From the late Heian period onwards, the position became hereditary, monopolized by the Abe and Kamo families.

{{Japanese-history-stub}}
```
