The Onmyō Hakase was responsible for educating ten {{ill|Onmyōsei|ja|陰陽生|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōsei|qq=}} students. However, in {{ill|Tenpyō 2|ja|天平2年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpyō 2|qq=}} ({{ill|730|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/730|qq=}}), as part of efforts to strengthen the Onmyōryō, three of these students were designated as {{ill|Onmyō Tokugyōsei|ja|陰陽得業生|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyō Tokugyōsei|qq=}} and received stipends. These students were subsequently chosen for future positions as Onmyōji and Onmyō Hakase. Additionally, the Hakase was granted four chō (町) of {{ill|Shikiden|ja|職田|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikiden|qq=}} (allotted rice fields). 

Educational texts included {{ill|Shinsen Onmyōshō|ja|新撰陰陽書|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsen Onmyōshō|qq=}}, {{ill|Huangdi Jinkui Jing|ja|黄帝金匱経|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Huangdi Jinkui Jing|qq=}}, {{ill|Gogyō Daiyi|ja|五行大義|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gogyō Daiyi|qq=}}, [[:en:I Ching|I Ching]], and {{ill|Nangi|ja|難儀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nangi|qq=}}. 

During the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]] and early [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]], the position was typically held by members of the {{ill|Ōtsu clan|ja|大津氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtsu clan|qq=}}, {{ill|Yuge clan|ja|弓削氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yuge clan|qq=}}, and {{ill|Shigatake clan|ja|滋岳氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shigatake clan|qq=}}. In the mid-Heian period, the {{ill|Imibe clan|ja|惟宗氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imibe clan|qq=}}, {{ill|Abe clan|ja|阿倍氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe clan|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kamo clan|ja|賀茂朝臣氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo clan|qq=}} became prominent. From the late Heian period onwards, the position became hereditary, monopolized by the Abe and Kamo families.

